metadata.description:

There is little chance of a 'perfect' work of art. The small imperfections require reflection.Â 

The variation and randomness give the work some asymmetry, common in wabi-sabi esthetics. Because of a limited color palette and the simple shapes used,Â the works keep their simplicity (another principle of wabi-sabi). The noisy texture gives it someÂ roughness, indeed again a core principle of wabi-sabi.Â 

The colors are reminiscent of the 70s and 80s. Some think that everything was better in the past. The trick is to enjoy the moment.

Thinking about impermanence is sometimes uncomfortable, 'ongemak' in Dutch, but also valuable.Â

metadata.name: (kinder)Garden, Monuments #222
metadata.description:
When Yazid and Zancan started their fxcollab journey, they knew very little about each other. They learnt about their rich cultural differences, their complementary graphic styles, and a 7-hour timezone difference. What they did have in common was each had two kids about the same age (one a pair of girls, the other boys).

Every kid was born a builder; every kid likes to sit in nature. Itâ€™s their way of discovering the world and dreaming of their future accomplishments. While they marvel at the heights of the cities and monuments they construct out of stacks of cubes, parents marvel at their ability to elaborate an unlimited range of worlds out of a limited range of materials. 

This project celebrates the humble and versatile cube. A deceptively simple yet powerful object of play and learning, regardless of age, whether youâ€™re stacking them up in a sandbox, or learning 3D graphics for the first time. 

This project is dedicated to kids, those who were once children, to the dreamers and builders who still enjoy playing with cubes.

Coded in Vanilla JS, the project combines Yazid's iconic â€œHashed/Hatchedâ€ aesthetic incorporated into childhood wooden toy block structures, and Zancan's signature lush foliage and framework, which enables all iterations to be plottable.
 
Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to get a SVG file suited for plotters
- Click on the image to download a 4K resolution PNG

metadata.name: Connections - v2 #78
metadata.description:
Dear collectors,
Roots was originally published as Project #1374 on November 26, 2021.
(https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/1374)
Due to a technical issue, Project #1374 has been hidden from the site and is being replaced by this reissued version.

_______________________________
Lets connect?

Connections (v1) showed in the description of its previous version an outburst of Brazilian citizens dissatisfied with their loss of monetary power due to the corruption of their government.

Now, in more mature way, this project draws luminous connections made thanks to the encounter of colored particles of a flowfield inside a Voronoi diagram, whose transparency is mapped according to the animation, bringing smoothness and fading in the transitions. As a result, we have different population divisions of these particles, like civilizations entering conurbatory processes, photographed on a dark night.

Possible Features:
> Background: Night, Blood, Deep Ocean, Wine, Swamp and Steel.
> Line colors: Reggae, Cold, Neon and Nature.
> Connection Factor: 1, 3, 7 and 11.
> Particles: 222, 333, 888, 1111 and 2222.


Go to Live View window ("open live") and press 's' to save a PNG from your canvas.

'Future-jazz-geometry' â†’ propulsive syncopated visual rhythms, polyphonic ensemble playing, varying degrees of improvisation, and often deliberate distortions of pitch and timbre.

metadata.name: RULES (for Elementary Cellular Automata) #346
metadata.description:
An important element of generative art is emergence. The most famous algorithm for this is probably Cellular Automata (CA).

However, numerous generative artists have created works using CA, which has lost its visual freshness and is like chewing gum that has lost its taste.

Although it is such a classic algorithm, adding my own little ideas to it and finding a new "flavor" is the reason why I code.

Here, the subject is 1D Elementary Cellular Automata, the simplest of all cellular automata. 1D Elementary Cellular Automata has 256 different rules, which change the shapes produced. This work aims to create more complex shapes by randomly selecting some of those rules and placing multiple of them on the screen.

The on/off of the CA cell is often likened to the behavior of living creatures.As of 2022, in the country where I live, prices are rising, wages are not increasing, and COVID-19 has not yet ended. I created this work with the image of people at the mercy of these various rules.

---

Screen click: Change rules
S key: Save png
L key: Show/hide grid

metadata.description:

Halftone is a term that can refer to both a technology used in image processing and as the synonym for semitone in music. A jazz musician Oliver Nelson released the album The Blues and the Abstract Truth in 1961. It is considered one of the most significant records of its time. In addition, he wrote Patterns for Improvisation, a hugely popular jazz patterns book. The MoirÃ© pattern design is on the book's cover.

metadata.name: BWEEPS  #324
metadata.description:
A minimalist, black-and-white generative profile picture (PFP) created to commemorate one-year anniversary of Bwople project by Gengoya. The artwork is derived from an initial sketch of Bwople which, despite being not the one that was chosen, still managed to captivate interests. The project provides a unique glimpse into an alternate universe in which Bwople could have been represented.

All images are hand-drawn work by Gengoya and composed by Vector Recite using PureSpider's fxhash-pfp maker tool.

To download the full size image on fx(hash):
- Click "open" below the image
- Left click on the image, a "Download image" button will appear on the bottom right.
- Click the "Download image" button.
